to show that these diverse roles are inseparable, woven together not only by the crisis of the Depression, but also by the pressures of bourgeoning consumerism. As the decade’s two major cultural forces, Esperdy concludes, consumerism and the Depression transformed the storefront from a seemingly insignificant element of the built environment into a potent site for the physical and rhetorical staging of recovery and progress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommercial buildingszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew Deal, 1933-1939. 0aStorefrontszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aland use planning, building types, depression history of the us, modernization credit plan, urban business districts, city spaces, small-town commercial strips, cultural, culture, social issues, modernized storefronts, federal provisions, public consumption, stagnant construction industry, architectural styles, architecture, european modernist design, landscape, bourgeoning consumerism, rhetorical staging, economic recovery, progress, economics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022621800740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226218021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226218021/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles